**Discord Bot with Ban Command using Discord.js v14**
=====================================================

### Prerequisites

*   Node.js (14 or higher)
*   Discord.js v14
*   A Discord bot token (create one on the [Discord Developer Portal](https://discord.com/developers/applications))

### Code

```javascript
// Import required modules
const { Client, CommandInteraction, SlashCommandBuilder } = require('discord.js');
const client = new Client({ intents: ['Guilds', 'GuildMessages'] });

// Define the ban command
const banCommand = new SlashCommandBuilder()
    .setName('ban')
    .setDescription('Ban a member from the server')
    .addStringOption(option =>
        option.setName('member')
            .setDescription('The member to ban')
            .setRequired(true)
    )
    .addStringOption(option =>
        option.setName('reason')
            .setDescription('The reason for the ban')
            .setRequired(false)
    );

// Register the ban command
client.commands.set(banCommand.toProperObject());

// Event listener for interactionCreate
client.on('interactionCreate', async interaction => {
    if (!interaction.isCommand()) return;

    // Handle the ban command
    if (interaction.commandName === 'ban') {
        const member = interaction.options.getString('member');
        const reason = interaction.options.getString('reason') || 'No reason provided';

        // Get the guild and member objects
        const guild = interaction.guild;
        const targetMember = await guild.members.fetch(member);

        // Check if the member exists
        if (!targetMember) {
            await interaction.reply({ content: 'Member not found', ephemeral: true });
            return;
        }

        // Ban the member
        await targetMember.ban({ reason });

        // Send a success message
        await interaction.reply({ content: `Member ${member} has been banned for ${reason}`, ephemeral: false });
    }
});

// Login to Discord with the bot token
client.login('YOUR_BOT_TOKEN');
```

### Explanation

*   We create a new Discord client instance with the required intents.
*   We define the ban command using the `SlashCommandBuilder`.
*   We register the ban command with the client.
*   We listen for the `interactionCreate` event and handle the ban command.
*   We get the guild and member objects, check if the member exists, and ban the member if they do.
*   We send a success message to the channel.

### Example Use Case

*   To use the ban command, type `/ban <member> [reason]` in a Discord channel where the bot has permission to ban members.
*   Replace `<member>` with the member's username or ID, and `[reason]` with the reason for the ban (optional).

### Note

*   Make sure to replace `YOUR_BOT_TOKEN` with your actual bot token.
*   This code assumes you have the necessary permissions to ban members in the server.

**Markdown to HTML Conversion Function**
=====================================

The following C++ function uses the `pugixml` library to convert markdown formatted text to HTML.

### Prerequisites

*   Install the `pugixml` library using your package manager or by downloading it from the official website.
*   Include the `pugixml.hpp` header file in your project.

### Code

```cpp
#include <pugixml.hpp>
#include <string>

/**
 * Converts markdown formatted text to HTML.
 *
 * @param markdown The markdown formatted text to convert.
 * @return The HTML formatted text.
 */
std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    pugi::xml_document doc;
    pugi::xml_parse_result result = doc.load_string(markdown.c_str());

    if (!result) {
        // Handle parsing errors
        return "";
    }

    pugi::xml_node root = doc.document_element();
    std::string html;

    // Convert markdown to HTML
    for (pugi::xml_node node = root.first_child(); node; node = node.next_sibling()) {
        if (node.type() == pugi::node_element) {
            pugi::xml_node child = node.first_child();
            while (child) {
                if (child.type() == pugi::node_text) {
                    // Convert markdown text to HTML
                    std::string text = child.value();
                    // Remove markdown formatting
                    text.erase(std::remove(text.begin(), text.end(), '#'), text.end());
                    text.erase(std::remove(text.begin(), text.end(), '*'), text.end());
                    text.erase(std::remove(text.begin(), text.end(), '_'), text.end());
                    text.erase(std::remove(text.begin(), text.end(), '>'), text.end());
                    text.erase(std::remove(text.begin(), text.end(), '<'), text.end());
                    text.erase(std::remove(text.begin(), text.end(), '`'), text.end());
                    text.erase(std::remove(text.begin(), text.end(), '~'), text.end());
                    text.erase(std::remove(text.begin(), text.end(), '`'), text.end());
                    text.erase(std::remove(text.begin(), text.end(), '\\'), text.end());
                    text.erase(std::remove(text.begin(), text.end(), '|'), text.end());
                    text.erase(std::remove(text.begin(), text.end(), ' '),
                               text.end()); // Remove extra spaces

                    // Convert text to HTML
                    text = "<p>" + text + "</p>";
                    html += text;
                }
                child = child.next_sibling();
            }
        }
    }

    return html;
}
```

### Example Usage

```cpp
int main() {
    std::string markdown = "# Heading\n## Subheading\nThis is a paragraph.";
    std::string html = markdownToHtml(markdown);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This code defines a function `markdownToHtml` that takes a markdown formatted string and returns the equivalent HTML string. The function uses the `pugixml` library to parse the markdown text and convert it to HTML.

